The ONNX backend compiles, but requested unavailable execution providers can silently fall back to CPU, undermining the feature's device-selection contract and performance expectations.

Review comment:

- [P2] Warn when ORT falls back to CPU â€” /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/0.8.16-slice-10-20260708T192441Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-embedder/src/ort_bge.rs:209-210
  When `FATHOMDB_EMBED_DEVICE` requests a provider that cannot be registered at runtime (for example `rocm` with a CPU-only ORT dylib, or `directml` on Linux), this relies on `ort`'s non-fatal `with_execution_providers` fallback. But the dependency is built with `default-features = false` and only `load-dynamic`, so `ort`'s warning/error macros are compiled out unless its `tracing` feature is enabled; the requested GPU provider can therefore silently fall back to CPU. That breaks the intended loud fallback behavior and can make cross-vendor runs appear successful while running much slower on CPU.
